{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11420"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11420"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.5,0.11,0.29,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4055"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77083"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4055"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62589"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1590"},{"type":"tags","id":"2287"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44819"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77083"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset shortness of breath and chest pain. He received his first COVID-19 adenoviral vector vaccine five days ago. He has a medical history of hyperlipidaemia and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His regular medications are atorvastatin and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E On examination, he appears distressed with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His chest is clear to auscultation and heart sounds are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would most strongly suggest vaccine-induced immune thrombotic thrombocytopenia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal D-dimer level","Platelet count of 40 x 10^9/L","Pulmonary embolism on CT pulmonary angiogram","Onset of symptoms two days post-vaccination","ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a potential vaccine-induced immune thrombotic thrombocytopenia (VITT), a rare but serious complication of adenoviral vector COVID-19 vaccines. The diagnostic criteria for VITT include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnset 4-42 days after adenoviral vector COVID-19 vaccination\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThrombocytopenia (platelet count \u0026lt;150 x 10^9/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPositive anti-PF4 antibodies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMarkedly elevated D-dimer (\u0026gt;4 times upper limit)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThrombosis (often in unusual sites)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore a \u003Cstrong\u003Eplatelet count of 40 x 10^9/L\u003C/strong\u003E would be highly suggestive of VITT in this clinical context. Severe thrombocytopenia is a hallmark feature of VITT and distinguishes it from other causes of post-vaccination symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal D-dimer level\u003C/strong\u003E would argue against VITT, as markedly elevated D-dimer (\u0026gt;4 times upper limit of normal) is characteristic of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolism on CT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E could be consistent with VITT, thrombosis alone is not specific as it can occur in many other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnset of symptoms two days post-vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E would be too early for VITT, which typically develops 4-42 days after vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest an inferior myocardial infarction, which would be a separate process from VITT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of confirmed VITT involves avoiding heparin-based anticoagulants and platelets, using alternative anticoagulation, and administering intravenous immunoglobulin. Plasma exchange may be considered in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vaccine-induced immune thrombotic thrombocytopenia (VITT) typically presents 4-42 days after adenoviral vector COVID-19 vaccination with thrombosis and thrombocytopenia.","The diagnosis of VITT requires thrombocytopenia, elevated D-dimer, thrombosis, and positive anti-PF4 antibodies.","VITT management involves non-heparin anticoagulation and immunomodulation with intravenous immunoglobulin."],"references":["Thrombosis and Haemostasis society of Australia and New Zealand. Suspected Vaccine Induced Prothrombotic Immune Thrombocytopenia (VIPIT)/Vaccine induced immune thrombotic thrombocytopenia VITT) THANZ Advisory Statement for Haematologists [Internet]. Australia: THANZ; 2021 [updated 2021 Dec 18; cited 2022 Jan 23]. Available from: https://www.thanz.org.au/documents/item/591","Patriarcheas V, Pikoulas A, Kostis M, Charpidou A, Dimakakos E. Heparin-induced Thrombocytopenia: Pathophysiology, Diagnosis and Management. Cureus. 2020 Mar 24;12(3):e7385. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32337112/","Klok FA, Pai M, Huisman MV, Makris M. Vaccine-induced immune thrombotic thrombocytopenia. Lancet Haematol. 2022 Jan;9(1):e73\u201380. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanhae/article/PIIS2352-3026(21)00306-9/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62589"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11420"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62589"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T08:52:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T08:52:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4055"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77083"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positio